        <!--?lit$351812512$--><div class="parts">
      <!--?lit$351812512$--><!----><colab-composer-markdown><template shadowrootmode="open"><!----><div><span><p>The hyperparameters used for the custom Logistic Regression model were:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong><code>learning_rate=0.001</code></strong>: This controls the step size at each iteration while moving towards a minimum of a loss function. A smaller learning rate can lead to better convergence but takes longer, while a larger one can converge faster but might overshoot the minimum.</li>
<li><strong><code>n_iterations=5000</code></strong>: This is the number of times the gradient descent algorithm will update the model's weights. More iterations can lead to better fitting, but too many can lead to overfitting or unnecessary computation if convergence is already reached.</li>
</ul>
<p>For scikit-learn's Logistic Regression model, the key hyperparameters were:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong><code>solver='liblinear'</code></strong>: This specifies the algorithm to use for optimization. 'liblinear' is a good choice for smaller datasets and supports L1 and L2 regularization.</li>
<li><strong><code>max_iter=2000</code></strong>: This sets the maximum number of iterations for the solver to converge. Similar to <code>n_iterations</code> in our custom model, it prevents the training from running indefinitely if convergence is slow.</li>
</ul>
<h3>Importance of Hyperparameter Tuning</h3>
<p>Hyperparameter tuning is crucial because hyperparameters are not learned from the data like model parameters (weights and biases). Instead, they are set <em>before</em> the training process begins and directly influence how well a model learns and performs. Here's why it's important:</p>
<ol>
<li><strong>Optimal Performance</strong>: Different datasets and problems require different hyperparameter settings for a model to achieve its best possible performance (e.g., highest accuracy, precision, recall, or lowest error). Without tuning, a model might perform suboptimally.</li>
<li><strong>Preventing Overfitting/Underfitting</strong>: Hyperparameters like learning rate, number of iterations, or regularization strength (often present in scikit-learn's Logistic Regression) directly impact the model's complexity and its ability to generalize. Proper tuning helps balance bias and variance, preventing the model from being too simple (underfitting) or too complex (overfitting) for the data.</li>
<li><strong>Stability and Convergence</strong>: For iterative algorithms like Gradient Descent, hyperparameters such as the learning rate and number of iterations are vital for stable convergence to a good solution. Incorrect values can lead to slow training, oscillations, or failure to converge at all (as was initially seen with the high and erratic cost in the custom model).</li>
<li><strong>Resource Optimization</strong>: Tuning can help find the right balance between model performance and computational cost. For instance, too many iterations or an overly complex model (due to hyperparameter choices) can lead to unnecessarily long training times.</li>
</ol>
<p>In essence, hyperparameter tuning helps ensure that the machine learning model is configured to learn effectively from the training data and generalize well to unseen data.</p></span></div></template>
